observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the:
Municipal Mayor, as agency head, (a) ensure utmost compliance with the provisions of COA-DBM-DILG-GCG-DND Joint Circular No. 2015-01 dated January 8, 2015 with emphasis on the completeness and propriety of supporting documents for the grant of CAs for CF and adherence to the procedural guidelines in the grant and liquidation thereof. The liquidation report for the CAs for CF shall be submitted directly to the Intelligence and Confidential Fund Audit Unit (ICFAU) of the COA;
Municipal Accountant (a) dutifully observe the submission to the Audit Team of cash advance vouchers for CF and other pertinent documents within seven (7) days from the release of check; (b) check the regularity and completeness of supporting documents for the cash advance for CF before its processing; and (c) submit to the Audit Team the supporting documents for the cash advance of SDO Calinawan drawn under Check No. 376211 dated September 24, 2021 to avoid suspension in audit.

We recommended that the:
Municipal Mayor, as the agency head, through the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) ensure utmost compliance with the provisions of Republic Act No. 9184, its Revised IRR and other relevant GPPB issuances on the procurement of goods, particularly on the preparation of BAC resolution recommending award of contract and the issuance of NOA, among others;
OIC-Municipal Accountant, BAC and the General Services Officer submit to the Audit Team (i) the lacking supporting documents for further evaluation of the transactions pursuant to Section 4 (6) of Presidential Decree No. 1445; and (ii) the distribution list duly acknowledged by the recipients of relief goods;
BAC (i) ensure that NOA, PO/Contract and NTP, if necessary, are posted in the PhilGEPS portal,  LGU’s website, if any, and in any conspicuous places within the Municipality and attach to the DV any proof of posting thereof; and (ii) maintain updated eligibility documents of suppliers/contractor to have a ready rooster of legally, technically, and financially capable suppliers/contractors in case of alternative modes of procurement especially during times of emergency; and
OIC-Municipal Accountant diligently review the disbursement vouchers, with emphasis on the propriety and completeness of supporting documents, as part of its internal audit services.

We recommended that the:

LCE, as the agency head, (i) ensure utmost compliance with the provisions of Republic Act No. 9184, its Revised IRR and GPPB issuances on the procurement of goods; (ii) submit a written justification on the unit cost of procured ladles as well as the noted discrepancy in the unit cost of rice that resulted in ₱1,216,000.00 difference between the contract amount per PO and the amount paid to the supplier; (iii) ensure that the PO is duly accomplished with complete and clear details regarding the specifications of the goods to be procured before its approval; and (iv) refrain from granting cash advances for payment of goods that could otherwise be paid thru checks in line with the principle of  imprest system;

OIC-Municipal Accountant and the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) submit to the Audit Team the lacking supporting documents for further evaluation of the transactions pursuant to Section 4 (6) of Presidential Decree No. 1445;

Members of the BAC (i) ensure that NOA, PO/Contract and NTP, if necessary, are posted in PhilGEPS/GPPB Online Portal or any other online platforms that may be required for the purpose and likewise attach any proof of posting of the same to the LGU’s website and conspicuous places within the Municipality; and (ii) continue to require updated file of its supplier to facilitate determination of legally, technically, and financially capable supplier and contractor in case of alternative modes of procurement especially during times of emergency; 

OIC-Municipal Accountant diligently review the disbursements, with emphasis on the propriety and completeness of supporting documents, as part of the Accounting Office’s internal audit service; and

Municipal Treasurer submit the proof of payment for the purchase of medicines and vitamins paid under Check No. 353388.

We recommended that the:

Municipal Mayor (i) provide reasonable justification/s on the Municipality’s spending of ₱8,241,070.40 for Christmas-related activities; (ii) stop the granting of cash advances for the procurement of goods; (iii) ensure strict compliance with the provisions of R.A. No. 9184 and its Revised IRR; and (iv) ensure economical and efficient utilization of government funds and to focus on the delivery of essential programs and projects that are more beneficial to its constituents; 

Members of the BAC (i) consolidate requisitions of the same items needed at or about the same time and stop the practice of splitting of contracts it being prohibited under Section 54.1 of R.A. 9184 and its IRR; and (ii) judiciously plan the procurement activities for the timely delivery of the Municipality’s operational requirements;

SDO concerned immediately return the full amount of ₱34,207.00 representing the excessive claims in her liquidations; and

OIC-Municipal Accountant properly review the transaction documents for disbursements and liquidations and ensure the validity and accuracy of the claims before these are processed and allowed for payment.

We recommended for the management to ensure that:
Job orders only cover piece of work or intermittent job requiring special or technical skills of short duration not exceeding six months;
Job order payrolls are supported by duly verified accomplishment reports; wages of personnel performing administrative, clerical and utility works are recorded to proper Personal Services accounts as prescribed in COA Circular 2015-009; and
Wages of personnel which are PS in nature should not be charged against the appropriations for MOOE;
In addition, the Management should provide a basis or justification for the varying and increasing rates of the job order employees. The management should also study the present organizational structure of the Municipality taking into consideration the LGU’s service requirements and make sure that unnecessary and overlapping functions with those of the permanent employees are eliminated. Also, judiciousness in the hiring of casual, contractual and job order personnel should be observed, taking into account the austerity measures prescribed by the government. Lastly, the Municipality should immediately stop the practice of utilizing the 20% Development Fund for the payment of personal services expenditures and adhere strictly with the DILG-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017.
